sequences are far-reaching for society, families, and individuals. Drawing on personal accounts and a broad knowledge of Ugandan culture and history, the essays in this collection explore ART from the perspective of those who received second chances. Their concerns about treatment, partners, children, work, food, and bodies reveal the essential sociality of Ugandan life. The collection is based on research undertaken by a team of social scientists including both Western and African scholars.Contributors. Phoebe Kajubi, David Kyaddondo, Lotte Meinert, Hanne O. Mogensen, Godfrey Etyang Siu, Jenipher Twebaze, Michael A. Whyte, Susan Reynolds Whyte  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAIDS (Disease)xPatientszUganda. 0aHIV-positive personszUganda. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aKyaddondo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtyang Siu, Godfrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMogensen, Hanne O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTwebaze, Jenipher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinert, Lotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhyte, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKajubi, Phoebe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds Whyte, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhyte, Susan Reynolds, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375975zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyte